    Demo Task 01 - Investigate request scope (Open / Investigation)
    ====================================================================

    Synthetic seed record for the case-management POC scoped application.
    This file is the FIRST of the 8-task demo dataset; together with
    tasks 02-08, it satisfies the AAP requirement (Section 0.7.4) of
    providing demo tasks that exercise the resolve-blocker and resolve-
    success gates on both case-type flows. The complete 8-task fixture
    matrix:

        Task 01 - Open        / Investigation / parent case 03 (In Progress GI)        ## THIS FILE
        Task 02 - Closed      / Review        / parent case 03 (In Progress GI)
        Task 03 - Open        / Follow-up     / parent case 04 (Pending GI)
        Task 04 - Closed      / Review        / parent case 05 (Resolved GI)
        Task 05 - Closed      / Other         / parent case 05 (Resolved GI)
        Task 06 - In Progress / Investigation / parent case 08 (In Progress Complaint)
        Task 07 - Open        / Investigation / parent case 08 (In Progress Complaint)
        Task 08 - Closed      / Review        / parent case 09 (Resolved Complaint)

    The 8-task dataset thus exercises:
      * All 4 task types - this task is the FIRST of FOUR Investigation-
        typed demonstrators (tasks 01, 02 on case 03 use Investigation
        in the original 8-task plan; the agent prompt for THIS file
        specifies type Investigation for the open-investigation child
        of case 03; tasks 06 and 07 are also Investigation on case 08).
        Per AAP Section 0.5.7 the case_task type Choice list defines
        exactly four values - Investigation, Review, Follow-up, Other -
        and Investigation is the FIRST value, positioned as the
        canonical fact-gathering activity that drives a case from its
        Open intake through the body of investigative work that
        ultimately produces a resolution. The "Investigate request
        scope" subject makes this lifecycle role explicit: the agent
        is performing the deeper investigation that defines the
        substance of case 03's In Progress phase.
      * All 3 task statuses (Open, In Progress, Closed) - this task
        contributes the FIRST of two Open tasks (the other being
        task 03 on case 04 with type Follow-up). The Open status is
        the initial, not-yet-started status that signals the agent
        has scheduled the work but has not yet begun execution. THIS
        task's Open status is THE LOAD-BEARING DEMONSTRATION that the
        validate_resolved_transition subflow's GlideRecord query
        addQuery('status', '!=', 'Closed') correctly identifies non-
        Closed children as resolve-blockers. Pairing this Open task
        with sibling task 02 (Closed) on the same parent case 03
        creates the canonical blocker pair: case 03 has TWO child
        tasks but only ONE blocker (this task), proving the gate
        filters by status rather than counting all child tasks.
      * 5 unique parent cases (03, 04, 05, 08, 09) - this task is the
        FIRST child of case 03 (In Progress General Inquiry). With
        sibling task 02 (Closed), case 03 has EXACTLY ONE non-Closed
        child task (this task). The case-03 fixture is the canonical
        demonstration of the General Inquiry resolve-BLOCKER path:
        when the operator attempts case 03 In Progress -> Resolved,
        the validate_resolved_transition subflow finds THIS row in
        its GlideRecord query and aborts the transition with the
        verbatim error "All tasks must be closed before resolving
        this case." THIS TASK IS THE CANONICAL RESOLVE-BLOCKER
        ANCHOR for the entire 8-task dataset; without this Open task
        the General Inquiry blocker path could not be exercised.
      * Both flow paths (General Inquiry and Complaint) - this task
        sits on a General Inquiry case (case 03). The General Inquiry
        flow's resolve-BLOCKER path is exercised by this Open task
        on case 03; the Complaint flow's resolve-BLOCKER path is
        exercised by tasks 06 (In Progress) and 07 (Open) on case 08;
        the General Inquiry flow's resolve-SUCCESS path is exercised
        by tasks 04 + 05 (both Closed) on case 05; the Complaint
        flow's resolve-SUCCESS path is exercised by task 08 (Closed)
        on case 09. THIS task is THE General Inquiry blocker anchor.
      * Both resolve outcomes (BLOCKED via at least one non-Closed
        task, and SUCCESS via zero non-Closed tasks) - this task
        directly enables the BLOCKED outcome on case 03. Per AAP
        Section 0.5.5 the General Inquiry flow's resolve-blocker
        behavior MUST surface the exact verbatim error message
        "All tasks must be closed before resolving this case." (per
        AAP Section 0.7.4) when the operator attempts In Progress ->
        Resolved with this Open task as a child of the parent case.

    Lifecycle position - WHY Open / Investigation / parent General
    Inquiry case In Progress is meaningful:
      Per AAP Section 0.5.5 the resolve gate's GlideRecord query
      executed inside the validate_resolved_transition subflow is:

          var gr = new GlideRecord('x_casemgmt_case_task');
          gr.addQuery('case', current.sys_id);
          gr.addQuery('status', '!=', 'Closed');
          gr.query();
          if (gr.next()) {
              // BLOCK: surface the verbatim error message
              //   "All tasks must be closed before resolving this case."
          } else {
              // ALLOW: zero non-Closed tasks - case may be Resolved
          }

      Case 03 is in In Progress status with type=General Inquiry. With
      sibling task 02 (Closed) plus THIS task 01 (Open), the query
      "case = case 03 AND status != Closed" returns ONE row (THIS task -
      task 02 is filtered out by the status != Closed qualifier). The
      subflow blocks any attempt to transition case 03 to Resolved and
      surfaces the verbatim error "All tasks must be closed before
      resolving this case." THIS TASK IS THE CANONICAL ROW THAT
      TRIGGERS THE BLOCKER. After an operator manually closes this
      task (status Open -> status Closed), the resolve gate's query
      returns ZERO rows and the In Progress -> Resolved transition is
      allowed.

      The Investigation task type captures the agent's primary fact-
      gathering activity - the substantive investigative work that
      defines what an "in-progress" case feels like operationally.
      Per the AAP's Section 0.5.7 Choice list for case_task type,
      Investigation is the first of four values (Investigation,
      Review, Follow-up, Other), positioned to capture the body of
      work between case intake (Open transition) and case resolution
      (Resolved transition). The "Investigate request scope" subject
      makes this lifecycle role explicit: the agent has been assigned
      the case and is now defining/executing the scope of the
      investigation that will produce the case outcome.

      The Open status is consistent with this not-yet-completed
      semantic: the agent has scheduled the investigation, has begun
      preliminary preparation (sibling task 02's initial review is
      already Closed indicating the agent has decided what scope to
      pursue), but has not yet finished the substantive investigative
      work. The status will progress to Closed once the investigation
      concludes, at which point the resolve gate on case 03 unblocks
      and the case may be transitioned to Resolved.

      The +5 day due_date (2026-05-06, relative to the build environment
      date 2026-05-01) reflects that this investigation work is
      scheduled to complete five days from now - a near-term, time-
      sensitive activity that is NOT yet overdue. The relative date
      pattern uses positive offsets (5 days hence) for active,
      scheduled tasks, consistent with Open status semantics (a task
      that has been scheduled but not yet started, with a target
      completion date in the near future). Per the agent prompt for
      this file, the +5 day window is also LOAD-BEARING for the
      dashboard's "My Overdue Tasks" report contract: the date
      qualifier (due_date < today) is NOT satisfied (2026-05-06 is in
      the future relative to today 2026-05-01), so this task
      correctly does NOT appear on the Agent Workspace's "My Overdue
      Tasks" widget. This demonstrates that the report's date filter
      correctly excludes future-dated active tasks rather than
      flagging them as overdue. The +5 day offset positions this task
      as a not-yet-overdue Open task - present, active, blocking the
      resolve gate, but not yet flagged as past due.

